To disable the alert box after filling the fields in a form using jQuery, you can remove the code that triggers the alert box from your script. Alternatively, you can use the jQuery `unbind()` function to remove the event handlers that trigger the alert box. Here's an example:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  // Bind an event handler to the form submit button
  $('#myForm').submit(function(event) {
    // Check if all fields are filled
    if ($('#name').val() == '' || $('#email').val() == '' || $('#message').val() == '') {
      // Show alert box if not all fields are filled
      alert('Please fill out all fields');
      event.preventDefault();
    }
  });

  // Disable the alert box by unbinding the submit event handler
  $('#myForm').unbind('submit');
});
```

In the above example, we first bind an event handler to the submit button of the form (`#myForm`). This event handler checks if all fields are filled and shows an alert box if not. We then disable the alert box by unbinding the `submit` event handler from the form using the `unbind()` function. This way, the alert box will not be triggered anymore when submitting the form.

